segments.text: you with?
Well, almost anything.
Many of them had their own big paddles, like a baseball bat that they smoothed off.
We were supposed to get them to sign a paddle in Christmas.
So I took a board about so long and made it in the shape of a fish and got them to sign it.
And a lot of them thought that was the paddle I was supposed to be paddling with, and it wasn't.
So they gave the wrong impression that I was getting a small paddle.
So we got that straightened out.
But I did keep that fish paddle signed for a long time.
And then it disappeared.
As you move around, you can do these things.
What else have we left out that
We left any people out?
Well, let me think now.
Who are some people, you mentioned Mr. Hensel, who are some other people for whom you feel gratitude for your A&M years?
My A&M years, of course.
Your student years.
Student years.
All right.
Charles Ratoon Brooks in architecture I like very much.
He's the only one that didn't treat me like a foreigner over there.
We were taking architecture courses as landscape art students, and a lot of them didn't think we had to mention being over there.
But he didn't.
And he was such a wonderful teacher that I took everything he had, every course he had, in history of architecture.
And then we had a senior inspection trip.
in the class of 37-38, I was in class 37.
We went on a bus trip to Natchez in New Orleans, and Mr. Brooks went along with us to lecture us on architecture.
And we didn't have enough money to pay for the bus, so two ladies from Hearn went with
Oh, my.
And we had quite a time.
But we got to Natchez, and I'm telling you now, we went to the first Confederate ball at Natchez, Mississippi.
And Mrs. Grace Grafton Miller, that's that thing that I went to.
And so we went to the first Confederate ball I had, and somebody decided that at the Grand March, these boys in uniforms should be in it.
So I went.
So you Aggies were part of the?
Confederate Ball Grand March in Natchez, Mississippi for the Natchez Pilgrimage.
And I remember that we were riding quad trains on the bus for entertainment.
Brooks wrote one.
It was raining when we left.
He says, I thought we were rather dippy, starting from Mississippi, with the weather so drippy.
But after Natchez and the romance of Natchez, there's nothing that matches Natchez.
Weepy.

So years later, I'm at a National Council of Garden Clubs meeting in Biloxi, and I go up to, this lady's there, the receiver of the ward, so I went up there to talk to her, and I says, I said, do you remember that bunch of cadets?
And I remember that little poem, I said, we wrote some quatrains, and here's one of them.
So I wrote, I recited that poem that I won at,
and she says, I want you to write that down.
She said, if you'll let us come back to Natchez any time, I'll put you up in the big house.
I'd have to get back in the big house, but you'd have to climb a ladder to get in the bed in that thing.
But they got us a date with one of those bell, those skirts, and we got to see the inside of a house, and one of us,
They have the living quarters and the show quarters.
And that was quite an experience.
I had some rather interesting experiences along the line, but they've all been fun.
Let's see.
I see in my notes I didn't ask about Bonfire.
What was Bonfire like when you were an undergraduate?
I was trash on the drill field, on the present drill field.
And where did y'all gather that trash?
All over the county.
People would come down the next morning and pick out what they thought was there and take it back home.
And if they didn't get it back the next night, just a pile of trash is all right.
Now, I've understood that there's usually a privy, an outhouse.

uh... whose job was it to grab the outhouse and and that would not be donated willing that would have been acquired uh... what else if we left out of your student days still i had more from the freshman
Just because I wanted to.
I wasn't afraid of the sophomores.
I didn't know they were piss-heads, as we called them.
And I wasn't afraid of them.
And I didn't care.
I wasn't afraid of them, but I didn't flaunt it in their face.
I made them learn everything they got out of me.
But it's all fun.
If you take all that in fun, it's great.
And I had tried to be a good freshman, and apparently I was, because I got to be a corporal my sophomore year.
And didn't everybody make corporal?
I was glad to be a squad leader, and that was part of the thing.
But anyway, I think I had more fun as a freshman at A&M than any freshman ever had.
You see, I lived in a room over there.
But I was supposed to put a note on my door if I went to the library or wherever I went.
And you're supposed to get somebody to sign that.
So finally they said, well, you just sign it and go on.
So I did.
So I went anywhere I wanted.
I went all over that campus.
And finally, some people came over.
Some upper class people came over to study with me.
Thought I was going to make a...
Good grade.
Never will forget Dr. Humber as long as I live.
In genetics.
I was taking genetics for the last term of my sophomore year.
And we were going to have a first big quiz.
And for some reason, he decided he'd read out people who had an A in the course.
And he read my name out.
I had the exam.
He handed my paper back to me and said, you better get busy.
I'd gotten mixed up on the first question, and instead of leaving it going on, I just stayed with it.
I made 35 on the first one.
So I worked all...
I just worked like the devil the rest of the years to get that down to a C. And I finally got it to a C. Boy, what a... And we had to count fruit flies up on top of the whole...
Well, the animal science building, the animal urban building, that was across the quadrangle from ag engineering.
We counted fruit flies until I thought we'd go crazy.
But anyway, that was part of the genetics.
Genetics was a good course, but I sure didn't flub on it.
I made it through, but I thought it was one of the hardest courses I had.
Next to soil.
Soil was a good course.
It was a hard course.
Dr. Jones, he's a good teacher.
OK, the last question for this morning session.
As you look back, what did it mean to your life that you attended Texas A&M?
Everything.
Once an Aggie, always an Aggie.
And of course, I discovered things there I'd never seen or heard of in my life.
When you grow up with that many women,
You're glad to get away.
For the first time in my life, I was with a man that I respected and loved and enjoyed being with.
I just thought that first year was just wonderful.
Let's start again.
Bob, would you summarize in a
comparatively short time, your experience between 1940 and when you come back to A&M in 68.
Yes, it was in Oklahoma under one president.
Well, but you went away to the war, had a distinguished war record.
Under distinguished.
I got shot out a few times.
I got wounded three times, lost the leg and sent home.
stepped on a mine 1.30 one morning, blew it off, laid there 27 hours before they picked me up, and rolled me off as killed in action.
But then I didn't get killed.
Well, then I see.
You worked at Baylor.
Well, I went to work at Baylor.
First in Baylor was a godsend.
I didn't know whether I could work a day or an hour
They didn't care.
They wanted somebody to fix that campus with Centennial and persuaded Patton Neff to hire me.
And there was nothing between Waco Hall and Patton Neff Hall except a sea of mud and two walks.
So I worked out the plan like I told you.
He said, build them, Rocker, build them.
I didn't have anybody to count them.
Anyway, that worked out.
We put the grass back, and they hadn't had grass before.
Then Baylor, Oklahoma, wanted me to come there.
And I told them I'd be glad to come, but I couldn't come until June the 1st, because I'd promised Baylor I'd stay there until the centennial started.
And they said, we'll wait.
So they did.
And that was 20 very wonderful, happy, professional years.
Our kids were all raised there.
Dr. and Ms. Cross were just the wonderful people to work for.
I think I told you about the trees.
I mentioned later that I had a project with the garden clubs to plant a million trees a year in the 51 organizations they had.
And they would make a million trees.
What am I saying?
Two million trees.
A million trees.
When they planted, they got busy and planted 108 million.
They really did a job on trees.
But we had people planting trees that had never seen or heard of how to plant a tree.
And a lot of them discovered new terms in trees.
It was good.
Now let's see, what did you...
Excuse me.
How did you...
come to A&M.
Who made the contact?
Tom Cherry came up to see me.
He came up to see the high-rise dorms on the campus and discovered what we called a small test garden.
And Earl Rudder had told, no, the board had told Earl Rudder they wanted flowers back on the campus and he could find them and they'd hire him.
So Ms.
Rudder put my name in the pot after we went to
All right, how did you and Mrs.
Rudder, how were you acquainted?
I was president of the Southwest Chapter of the American Society of Landscape Architects, and we had invited Ms. Lady Bird Johnson down to receive a citation.
She couldn't come to get it, so Mrs.
Rudder was going to receive it for her.
And we sat by each other all night.
She went back home and said, Earl, I found you a man.
And to make it brief, they hired me.
She put my name in the box.
All right, I'm not going to ask about salary any other time.
What was your beginning salary at A&M then?
Oh, that's why I want to know, $20,000.
And that's 1968.
See, I had just done the World Fan Project in New York for the governor of Oklahoma, and it turned out all right.
And...
But they called me, and I went down for an interview.
I mean, Morris Bloodworth called me to come down.
And anyway, to make a long story short, they offered me $20,000, and I talked to Mr. Rutter, I mean, Dr. Cross, and Dr. Cross said,
Don't look back.
Says, I'm resigning.
He says, July the 1st.
And the man they hired has never been in education.
He says, whoa, we don't know what you're going to do.
And Mrs. Cross, I had never seen her anyway, but dressed ready to go out on the street.
This woman, this is when I showed up in negligee.
I never saw anything but a negligee and barefooted.
And that was not the image of a college friend's wife.
And I knew I couldn't take that.
I was scared to death of that woman.
When you came to A&M in 1968, what was your assigned duty?
I was to be a professor of floriculture and have charge of the campus.
I was going to be the landscape architect on the,
not at the campus planning committee, but I ran into Paul Stevens, which if any plan, a campus plan was done, he was going to do it.
He bucked me on everything I tried to do all the way.
It was bad.
The greatest accomplishment I did was in the academics at his request, at Dr. Rodgers' request.
You see, horticulture, floriculture,
was a section of soil and crop sciences.
And it had been a flourishing department of agriculture before the war.
But things happened.
The war happened.
It deteriorated a lot.
And I was asked to rebuild.
Let me get it back in focus.
I was called over to Dr. Bloodworth's office, he was the head of the department, and said, they want you to take over floriculture in the morning.
And I said, okay, but my Lord, Mr. DeWorth knew about it.
Do you remember DeWorth?
Oh, Lord, that was a man.
He hated girls, first of all.
He didn't like students.
And he would let some of them come in.
Well, anyway...
I said, well, does DeWerth know about that?
He says, yes, he'll come over at 5.
I said, let me get out of here.
So I went home.
The next morning, he came in, and he laid 50-some-odd keys down on the desk without all the numbers and identification taken off of them.
He said, if you're going to run this thing, you're going to need the keys for it.
So I called Bloodworth.
I said, I believe he called me.
He says, how's it going?
I says, it's already started.
I said, I've got 50-some-odd keys laid down on my desk.
All the numbers and identifications have been filed off of them.
And he said, oh, I can take care of that real quick.
He picked up the phone and called physical, and he said, were all the locks and keys changed on every lock of the horticulture?
Oh, well, bye.
And then I told the secretary that they're changing all the locks on the .
She says, no, I know who has the key over here anyway.
I said, that's right.
I said, I have been permitted to have a key in two years that I've been here.
And he wouldn't let me have a key, would he?
So as a result, he didn't get a key, and he had to pay a deposit.
And it just killed his soul.
He would not pay for a deposit on the keys, any of the keys, because they were his greenhouses and all that.
And I had not been allowed in the greenhouses for years, I mean, the times I'd been there.
Anyway, it came that everybody had to put up a deposit and get the total security, and they had to check them out and put their security up.
Well, that didn't go over too good, but anyway, it went that way.

We had control of the department, and we got, apparently I did what they wanted done, because they called me in January and said, now, you've taken over Floriculture, we want you to take over all of Horticulture.
And I said, now look,
I'm the last man hired, low man on the totem pole.
I'm not a PhD.
You have nine PhDs up there.
But I said, it's not an academic problem.
It's a middle management problem.
You've got to tell people what they're going to do and do it.
So we redid all the horticulture.
We had 37 majors at Haskell at the time I got over there.
That's not enough to teach any class.
We had the practitioners everywhere.
Seven years later, I also was working on the master planning committee and knew when the buildings were coming.
And between Perry Atkinson and myself, we got $18 million for a new horticulture building.
Happened to be at the right place at the right time again.
And we had 540 majors.
That's actually that.
So we went from no department, or no section, not even a viable section, to a full-fledged department of horticulture, and a new building, and the buddy Ben's request of $2 million.
Again, I said I had to be in the right place at the right time, and knew what we had to do.
And I didn't ask anybody.
I would come over there, and I said,
I said, now, I'll do this job.
I know what you want done.
But unless those nine PhDs agree to it, I'm going to be the chief paper shuffler.
I don't want any part of it.
So all but one agreed.
By the way, OK, except one.
And he wasn't going to agree.
So they said, you either agree to let Rutgers do the paperwork, or you look for a new job.
So he stayed.
I didn't work as hard in my life on anything as I did that.
And we got the new building, we got Buddy Benz to grant, and the endowed chair and floor culture.
And again, I said, had I not come back to the NM, we'd never heard of Buddy Benz.
But that's, again, being in the right place at the right time, and moving, not just sitting still, and moving out.
Now, so as an academic, you were the department head and reported to the dean of agriculture.
We became a department.
No.
Oh.
No, no.
We built it from a very small section of 37 majors to a complete department.
But they thought they had to have a PhD to hit it.
So they had a nationwide search.
And we got a man who had not been in the academic field
Since he graduated from Clemson, I believe, 18 years before, had not been in an academic environment.
He did not know what even was up in academics.
And his main area of interest was garlic.
So did you.
But anyway, to make a long story short, we got a man whose interest was in garlic.
And he didn't know what to do.
Dr. Bloodworth, I mean, Dr. myself and Dr. in food science, there were three of us who were senior professors.
And we told him we'd do anything we wanted to do.
We'd be glad to help him do anything he wanted to do.
And so he'd call us in, and every time we'd make a recommendation, he'd do the opposite.
And every time he got his tail in a crack.
And I mean...
We had the 540 majors, and we lost 200 majors the first year he was there.
I never worked as hard in my life to get a department rebuilt and going in my life.
See, it didn't degenerate the way it did, go down.
But that's the hardest work I did for the president.
And it all became, and you see,
The first thing you knew, we went over fish-positive girls.
So Kunkel called me down and says, what are you going to do with all these girls?
I said, we're going to teach them.
Well, what are you going to teach them?
They don't want to be biochemists.
I said, no, no, they sure don't, Dean.
There's a whole other world out there besides biochemistry, and we're going to explore it.
I said, we'll start off with fly arranging first and get the buddy bins and books going.
And that's what we did.
And I
But I have never in my life worked this hard to get a program re-established and go in and I did that one.
And then we got this man, the garlic man, that finally they wouldn't even give him an army.
One day he says, can you stand on your head?
I said, stand on my head?
Well, why would I want to stand on my head?
Well, it's good for you.
It makes you think.
And so he just stood on his head.
And I thought, my god.
It's the best man to go down in the industry.
And it stands on its head, we were dead ducks.
That's all there is to it.
And that's what happened.
All right, now, in addition to the academic task, you were the chief campus planter.
To whom did you report in that responsibility?
That's another story.
They wanted me to take it over as a part of ground maintenance, I mean a physical plant.
I said, no dice.
I said, I can't go through 15 people and ever get heard
I either am in charge of the campus or I'm not in charge of it.
And so I said, OK. And they put me in the end part of my physical plan.
But I had my own budget in Maine.
First thing I knew, we had no money.
We didn't know.
I said, look, I can't go up to this anymore.
I'm sorry.
I'm either running this thing or I'm not running it.
And I'm not going to be here running a physical plan that knows not a damn thing about what's going on outside space.
He's concerned with inside space.
I expect he's equipped to handle that, but he doesn't know anything about outdoor space or how to handle it.
That's what it's all about.
I didn't think it easy, but I worked hard and got it done the way I wanted it done, but it was hard.
Now, to whom did you report?
Tom Cherry?
Tom Cherry.
Describe him as a leader, as an administrator.
Very good.
Excellent.
You know, his brother, Bob, would have represented us in the legislature.
But Tom Cherry was a gentleman and a scholar from way back.
I had no trouble with Tom.
I would just lay the cards on the table, and we'd go from there.
And it worked out for them.
I think Tom Sherry was one of the finest people I ever worked with.
Did he give you any directions, any boundaries?
I'd ask him for boundaries, and then I'd ask him, for instance, Clyde Freeman sent me a word one time that some student came to interview me about the ice return on the football field.
Well, part of it,
And I've never been to either request to give a student an interview in my life.
But his henchman, I forget his name now, came over and closed the door back of me and said, who gave you the privilege to write a student a story about the AstroTurf?
I said, nobody gave me that thing.
I said, that's part of the outdoor space I'm taking care of.
And I gave him the story.
He says, well, don't do it anymore.
I said, you're just crazy as hell.
If they want to stir, they're going to get one.
And I said, that's not the way I was raised, and that's not the way academic freedom is.
I said, don't you or your boss know anything about academic freedom?
He didn't reply to that, but they never did like the fact that I would take the leeway to do what I was supposed to do.
They wanted me to be under them, and I refused to do it.
That's the only way I got anything accomplished.
was to just do what I thought I was doing and tell him if he didn't like it, he could go to hell.
Now, when you first came, first arrived, did you have any clear direction?
Did Mr. Rutter tell you what he wanted done?
Yes and no.
You see, Mr. DeWorth just gave Ms. Rutter hell.
If she wanted a flower, she couldn't have it.
He didn't go out where the rodents were going.
And he accused her of cutting these rodents off test plots.
It was just pure hell.
And he thought he could get away.
And I didn't have to be told.
I saw it.
After we got to many girls, it was over 4% to 5% girls, he came in one day.
And last year, he was there.
He was head of this.
And I had such a bad year in my life.
Everything I did was wrong.
Came in one day and said, you're making a big mistake letting all these girls in here.
I said, I'm not letting any girls in here.
They're taxpayers' daughters, and they're just welding the fires in May.
We're not supposed to tell taxpayers they can't send their kids here.
That's the last thing we're going to do.
Anyway, I had a real rough time, because everything I did that year was wrong.
But I just didn't pay attention.
I ignored him and he'd grow on me.
I had to.
But now regarding Mr.
Rudder, did you have any direct interaction with him?
Yes.
Let me think.
When I came down for an interview, I talked to him, and he made me the offer of $20,000 a year and told me that I'd have charge of the campus.
and be a professor of floriculture.
And as each one grew, I had to keep pace with them.
But the only place I did, I think the best thing I ever did academically was rebuild horticulture into a viable department.
And I mean, it was a good one.
But the first time that Mr. Garlic showed up and stood on his head,
The kids dropped that thing like, of course, like nobody in business.
Now, to attract students, what did you and your colleagues do to attract more majors?
We talked to everyone that came on campus.
I said, I don't ever want to see a door closed and some kid timidly knocking on that door.
Because the bottom line is, when you don't have any students to teach, you don't have a job around here.
I said, students are number one priority at this place.
And I want you to understand, now
And I never want to see another door closing and somebody timidly knocking on it.
The whole time I stood there.
And I had one kid that I had to have him try to make an appointment.
I said, no, you keep that door open.
If he goes up there and knocks on the door, you let him in.
And we opened the door and said, you're welcome as you can be.
And Roy just jumped.
